{{For|other individuals with this name|Ahijah}}
[[File:Ahijahs and Jeroboam.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Gerard Hoet]], ''Ahijah's prophecy to [[Jeroboam]]'', 1728.]]

'''Ahijah the Shilonite''' ({{Hebrew Name 1|אחיה השילוני|Aḥiya <ref>According to [http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/980-ahijah-the-prophet "Ahijah", ''Jewish Encyclopedia''], the name also appears in the expanded form אחיהו, Aḥiyahu.</ref> ('brother of [[Jah|Yah]]'<ref>See Gesenius, who interprets the name as "friend of Jehovah," taking the literal expression 'brother' as metaphorical for friendship. [https://www.blueletterbible.org/lang/lexicon/lexicon.cfm?Strongs=H281&t=KJV]</ref>) Hashiloni)}},  was a [[Levite]] [[prophet]] of [[Shiloh (biblical city)|Shiloh]] in the days of [[Solomon]], as mentioned in the [[Hebrew Bible]]'s [[1 Kings]]. Ahijah foretold to [[Jeroboam]] that he would become king ({{bibleverse|1|Kings|11:29|HE}}).<ref name=je>[http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/980-ahijah-the-prophet "Ahijah", ''Jewish Encyclopedia'']</ref>

The [[Hebrew Bible]] records two of his prophecies. In {{bibleverse|1|Kings|11:31-39|HE}}, he announced the separation of the Northern ten tribes from Solomon's [[Kingdom of Israel (united monarchy)|united kingdom]], forming the [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Northern Kingdom]]. In {{bibleverse|1|Kings|14:6-16|HE}}, Ahijah's prophecy, delivered to [[Jeroboam's wife]], foretold the death of the king's son, the destruction of Jeroboam's dynasty, and the fall and [[Babylonian captivity|captivity]] of Israel "beyond the River", a stock expression for the land east of the [[Euphrates]].<ref>[http://www.studylight.org/dictionaries/hbd/b/beyond-the-river.html ''Holman Bible Dictionary,'' "Beyond the River"]</ref>

According to [[2 Chronicles]], Ahijah also authored a book, described as the ''Prophecy of Ahijah the Shilonite'', which contained information about Solomon's reign.<ref>{{bibleverse|2|Chronicles|9:29|HE}}</ref> This text, however, has not survived and is one of the [[Non-canonical books referenced in the Bible|lost texts]] mentioned in the [[Hebrew Bible]]. In {{bibleverse|1|Kings|11:41|NKJV}} it is referred to as the "[[Acts of Solomon|Book of the Acts of Solomon]]".

[[Rabbinic]] [[tradition]] credits Ahijah with having lived a very long life, linking his life-span with that of [[antediluvian]] [[patriarch]]s such as [[Methuselah]] and [[Adam]].<ref>Babylonian Talmud, [[Baba Batra]] 121b</ref>

