{{Psychology sidebar}}
The '''Life Events and Difficulties Schedule''' is a psychological measurement of the [[Stress (biology)|stressfulness]] of life events. It was created by [[psychologist]]s George Brown and Tirril Harris in 1978.<ref>{{cite book |year=1978 |title=Social origins of depression: A study of psychiatric disorder in women |location=London |publisher=Tavistock |isbn=0-422-76310-1 |first1=George William |last1=Brown |first2=Tirril |last2=Harris |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pmAhsL44_60C&printsec=frontcover}}</ref> Instead of accumulating the stressfulness of different events, as was done in the [[SRRS|Social Readjustment Rating Scale]] by Thomas Holmes and Richard Rahe, they looked at individual events in detail.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/0022-3999(67)90010-4 |last1=Holmes |first1=Thomas |last2=Rahe |first2=Richard |year=1967 |title=The Social Readjustment Rating Scale |journal=[[Journal of Psychosomatic Research]] | volume=11 |issue=2 | pages=213–218 |pmid=6059863}}</ref> The schedule is made up of an interview by which as much contextual information around the event as possible is collected. The event is then rated by "[[Blind experiment|blind]]" raters using this contextual information.

Critics of this method note the fact that the impact of the independent variable, the event itself, is measured by evaluating it using [[Mediation (statistics)|mediating]] and [[Moderation (statistics)|moderating]] variables.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}

==Research==

The Life Events and Difficulties Schedule proved a powerful instrument to predict changes in neuroticism.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Jeronimus, B.F.|author2= Riese, H.|author3= Sanderman, R.|author4= Ormel, J.|year=2014|title= Mutual Reinforcement Between Neuroticism and Life Experiences: A Five-Wave, 16-Year Study to Test Reciprocal Causation|journal= Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume=107|issue=4|pages=751–64|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1037/a0037009 | doi = 10.1037/a0037009|pmid=25111305}}</ref>

