'''Æthelwulf of Berkshire''' (before 825 – 4 January, 871) was a [[Saxon]] [[ealdorman]]. In 860 he and other men of Berkshire fought off a band of pirates near Winchester, Hampshire.<ref name="Points2013">{{cite book|author=Guy Points|title=The Combined Anglo-Saxon Chronicles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KskVBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA30|date=30 May 2013|publisher=Guy Points|isbn=978-0-9557679-2-0|pages=30–}}</ref> Later he mustered a force of 1400 men against an army of [[Danes (Germanic tribe)|Danes]], won the 31 December 870 [[Battle of Englefield]] on behalf of the then kingdom of [[Wessex]].<ref name="Venning2014">{{cite book|author=Timothy Venning|title=The Kings & Queens of Anglo-Saxon England|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-TaoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT119|date=30 January 2014|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|isbn=978-1-4456-2459-4|pages=119–}}</ref> He received a [[land grant]] in 843/44 from [[Brihtwulf]], king of [[Mercia]]; and lost his life at the [[Battle of Reading (871)|Battle of Reading]].<ref name="HighamHill2013">{{cite book|author1=N.J. Higham|author2=D.H. Hill|title=Edward the Elder: 899-924|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=phBUAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA113|date=11 October 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-34941-6|pages=113–}}</ref><ref name="Venning2013">{{cite book|author=Timothy Venning|title=The Anglo-Saxon Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7CgCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT72|date=19 February 2013|publisher=Pen and Sword|isbn=978-1-78346-894-2|pages=72–}}</ref>
[[Æthelweard (historian)|Æthelweard]], in his account of the battle, reveals a curious fact about Æthelwulf, master of the art of the [[ambush]]: he was a Mercian and not a West Saxon. Not only this, Æthelweard says:
"In fact, the body of the ''[[dux]]'' (leader) mentioned above was carried away secretly and taken into Mercia to the place called Northworthig, but [[Derby]] in the Danish tongue."<ref>Paul Hill (2009). ''The Viking Wars of Alfred the Great'', p. 41. {{ISBN|978-1-59416-087-5}}.</ref>
